[test codeintent]
# gen323 (TODO.md P1) — the code KEYHOLE, and the register guard that makes
# widening it safe.
#
# The code faculties were real (25/25 code-bench gates) but reachable only
# through an exact C phrasebook. In the 2026-07-12 conversation with F., the SAME
# snippet answered to "what functions does this define:" and walled on "explain
# what this does:" — one phrasing away. An agent whose analysis is reachable only
# by the magic words cannot receive a GitHub issue, which is the whole mission.
#
# The phrasings are now intent_cue facts (kb/core/intents.p0), so the surface
# grows at RUNTIME: a new way of asking costs a FACT, not a generation. These
# cases are the held-out phrasings — none of them existed as a C cue.

# --- explain: the phrasing that walled ---
> explain what this does: int sum(int n){ int s=0; for(int i=0;i<n;i++) s+=i; return s; }
< This is a C code snippet. It returns a value. It contains a loop.

# The loop is named: `for(` with no space used to be invisible to the explainer.
> what does this do: void swap(int *a, int *b) { int t = *a; *a = *b; *b = t; }
< This is a C code snippet.

# --- debug: "there is a bug in this code" was not a cue; "find the bug" was ---
> there is a bug in this code: int f(int n) { return n * 2 }
< Issue found: Missing semicolon at the end of a statement.

# --- case folding: copy_trim does not fold case, so a capital used to miss ---
> Is there a bug in: int g(void) { return 0; }
< I compiled it (cc -fsyntax-only) and it has no syntax errors. That is all I checked: I cannot yet tell you whether it computes what you intended.

# --- the REGISTER GUARD: widening the surface is only safe with this ---
# `is` is a Python keyword AND an ordinary English word, so a keyword tally alone
# made prose into code: "what language is this: the sky is blue" answered "This
# looks like Python code." Structural evidence must dominate (TASKLIST C14).
> what language is this: the sky is blue
< I can not identify the language. It does not look like C or Python to me.

# And a prose turn wearing a code question's clothes must NOT be claimed by the
# code module at all — it used to answer "I did not find obvious errors in this
# code snippet", which is a misclaim about what the turn even IS.
> what is wrong with this: the sky is blue
< I don't understand that yet.

